  "answer": "The critic's claim that the mechanism fails to name a specific causal institution or process is unfounded. The target explicitly identifies the institutional locus as 'scribal monopolies' within palace economies and specifies the causal process as the erosion of that monopoly through the 'diffusion of alternative accounting practices and merchant alphabets,' which triggered coordination failures across networked polities. The forbidden case of Ugarit abandoning alphabetic writing for cuneiform-only administration does not violate clause (1) because the target's mechanism does not assert that any single administrative technology (e.g., the alphabet) is necessary for collapse; rather, it is the loss of asymmetric information advantages by the scribal monopoly that drives collapse. A return to cuneiform-only administration in Ugarit could still represent a shift in information-control structures that is consistent with—or even an instance of—the very erosion of monopoly the mechanism describes, depending on whether that shift decentralized or disrupted the existing scribal monopoly's control over administrative knowledge. The target therefore provides a concrete institutional process (scribal monopoly and its erosion) and does not claim the reversal described in the forbidden case is impossible under its terms, so it does not violate clause (1) of std-hist."
